Here's an example React app file that can be used for a chat app:

```
import React, { useState, useEffect } from 'react';
import io from 'socket.io-client';

const socket = io('http://localhost:3000'); // Change to your server's port if different

function App() {
  const [messages, setMessages] = useState([]);
  const [newMessage, setNewMessage] = useState('');

  useEffect(() => {
    // Listen for incoming messages and add them to the state
    socket.on('new-message', (message) => {
      setMessages([...messages, message]);
    });
  }, [messages]);

  const handleFormSubmit = (event) => {
    event.preventDefault();
    if (newMessage.trim() !== '') {
      // Send the new message to the server
      socket.emit('new-message', {
        text: newMessage.trim(),
        timestamp: new Date().getTime(),
      });

      // Clear the input field
      setNewMessage('');
    }
  };

  return (
    <div className="App">
      <h1>Chat App</h1>
      <div className="messages">
        {messages.map((message, index) => (
          <div key={index} className="message">
            <span className="message-timestamp">
              {new Date(message.timestamp).toLocaleTimeString()}
            </span>
            <span className="message-text">{message.text}</span>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
      <form onSubmit={handleFormSubmit}>
        <input
          type="text"
          value={newMessage}
          onChange={(event) => setNewMessage(event.target.value)}
          placeholder="Type a message..."
        />
        <button type="submit">Send</button>
      </form>
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;
```

This React app defines a component named `App`. It uses state to keep track of the chat messages (`messages`) and the currently typed message (`newMessage`).

The `useEffect` hook is used to listen to incoming messages from the server using Socket.io. Whenever a new message is received, it is added to the `messages` state.

The `handleFormSubmit` function is called when the user submits a new message through the form. It sends the message text and a timestamp to the server using Socket.io (`socket.emit('new-message', ...)`). It also clears the `newMessage` state.

The component renders a list of messages in the `messages` state, along with a form to submit new messages. When the user types a message, the `onChange` handler updates the `newMessage` state, and when the form is submitted, the `onSubmit` handler calls the `handleFormSubmit` function.

Note that this is just a basic implementation of a chat app, and there are many other things you might want to add, such as user authentication, message persistence, or real-time updates when users join or leave the chat.

